[1] South Korea, 3 new cases, 2 new fatalities - MOH 22 Jun 2015
Date: 22 Jun 2015
Source: South Korean MOH - 22 Jun 2015 [trans. by Korean subscribers, edited]
http://www.mw.go.kr/front_new/al/sal0301vw.jsp?PAR_MENU_ID=04&MENU_ID=0403&page=1&CONT_SEQ=323637


MERS-CoV Daily Update
------------------------
-Total number of cases now stands at 172: 95 currently receiving treatment (55.2 percent), 50 discharged (29.1 percent), 27 dead (15.7 percent).
-3 additional case and 7 additional recoveries compared to previous day's numbers; 2 new fatalities.
-Of the 95 receiving treatment: 81 in stable condition (85.3 percent), 14 reportedly unstable (14.7 percent).
-80 have contracted the virus nosocomially, 59 have come in contact in-facility while visiting family, and 33 are of hospital personnel.

Overview of Confirmed Cases
- The Ministry of Health and Welfare's MERS-CoV Task Force has announced 3 new cases of MERS-CoV - bringing the total tally up to 172 - as of 6 AM KST, 22 Jun 2015.
- The number of total patients currently undergoing treatment has decreased by 6 since yesterday and currently stands at 95 (55.2 percent of total); 7 have recovered, bringing the number up to 50 (29.1 percent); the fatality count currently stands at 27 (15.7 percent).

New Cases
- 3 additional cases has been confirmed since yesterday [21 Jun 2015]
- Patient no. 170 (77 year old male) was hospitalized at Konkuk University Medical Center at the same time as Patient no. 76 on 6 Jun 2015.
- Patient no. 171 (60 year old female) was hospitalized at Seoul Samsung Medical Center ED from 27-29 May 2015
- Patient no. 172 is a caregiver employed by Daecheong Hospital.

New Dischargees
- Starting with Patient no. 67 (16 year old male) who is the only patient in their teens to date, Patients no. 22 (39 year old female), 49 (75 year old male), 55 (36 year old male), 68 (55 year old female), 130 (65 year old female), and 144 (71 year old male) have all been discharged in between 20 Jun 2015 and the morning of 21 Jun 2015, bringing the total number of recoveries to 50.
*Patient no. 67 has been cleared of MERS-CoV infection, but has currently been moved to a different ward for unrelated treatment.
- Dischargees underwent various courses of symptomatic treatments, such as antibiotic and anti-viral treatment. The patients were cleared for discharge after signs of respiratory distress and fever subsided, and confirmatory tests resulted negative.
- Of the 50 total recoveries, 28 (56.0 percent) are male with 22 (44.0 percent) being female; 14 have been in the 40s (28 percent), 8 each have been in their 50s and 60s (18 percent each), 7 patients have been in the 70s (14 percent), 6 have been in the 30s (12 percent), 4 have been in the 20s (8 percent), with 1 in the teens (2 percent).

New Fatalities
- Patients no. 101 (84 year old male) and 128 (87 year old male, AFIB (atrial fibrillation) / CHF (congestive heart failure / cancer / stroke) were pronounced dead on 21 Jun 2015 and on the morning of 22 Jun 2015, bringing the fatality count up to 27.
- Of the 27 reported fatalities to date, 20 have been male (74.1 percent), while 7 have been female (25.9 percent); in terms of age distribution, the lion's share of the fatalities have been in the 60s with 9 (33.3 percent) fatalities, followed by 8 (29.6 percent) fatalities in the 70s, 5 (18.5 percent) in the 80s, 4 (14.8 percent) in the 50s and 1 (3.7 percent) in the 40s.
- 25 of the 27 fatalities (92 percent) were elderly, immunocompromised, and/or suffering from pre-existing conditions such as COPD (chronic obstructive pulmonary disease - emphysema), cancer, cerebrovascular disease, and diabetes.

Modes of Transmission and Demographic Characteristics
- A categorical analysis on the modes of transmission of the 172 total cases reveals:
- Nosocomial infection is the most common mode of transmission at 46.5 percent (80 cases), infections as a result of hospital visits by family members comprise 34.3 percent of total cases (59), while infections of faculty and other medical personnel is report to be at 19.2 percent (33)

- Male infectees comprise 61 percent of the total cases (105), and females, 39 percent (67)
- Total distribution by age of all cases is as follows: 36 patients (20.9 percent) are in the 50s, 35 (20.3 percent) are in their 60s, 30 are in their 40s (17.4 percent), 28 are in their 70s (16.3 percent), while 26 are in their 30s (15.1 percent).

Isolations and Quarantine
- As of 22 Jun 2015 6 AM KST, 4035 are under quarantine with the reflected numbers being 5 percent lower than previous day's numbers (a decrease of 202); the total number of those released from quarantine has increased to 9331, which equates to an increase of 519 compared to previous day's numbers.
- Of the 3833 under quarantine, 3048 are under home isolation (a 7.5 percent decrease, or a decrease of 248), while the number of hospital quarantines has increased by 46 (6.2 percent), bringing the total number of hospital quarantines to 785.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[In the past 24 hours there have been 3 newly confirmed cases and 2 newly reported fatalities bringing the total number of MERS-CoV infected individuals reported by South Korea to 172 including 27 deaths (reported case fatality rate 15.7 percent).The number of recovered patients is now at 50 (29.1 percent). Of the 3 newly confirmed cases, one was a 4th generation case, one a 3rd generation case and the 3rd is still under investigation. Newly reported cases have contact dates in late May (27-29) and the 1st week in June (5-6), more than 14 days ago. Of the 172 reported cases, 31 (18 percent) are 2nd generation cases, 122 (70.9 percent) are 3rd generation cases, 15 (8.7 percent) are 4th generation cases and 1 (0.6 percent) is a 5th generation case.

Another sign that the outbreak is coming under control is the decreasing numbers of individuals in quarantine -- a sign that there are significantly fewer contacts of confirmed cases under quarantine/monitoring.

The HealthMap/ProMED map of South Korea can be found at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3454450,195. - Mod.MPP]

